elements.content: The hydrothermal reaction of (NH4)6Mo7O24·4H2O, CuCl2·2H2O, and 4,4‘-bipyridine yields bipyridine-ligated copper-trimolybdate monohydrate [Cu(4,4‘-bipy)(H2O)(Mo3O10)]·H2O in the monoclinic system with space group of C 2/c and cell parameters of a = 15.335(2) Å, b = 15.535(2) Å, c = 15.106(2) Å, β = 101.162(2)°, V = 3530.7(9) Å3, and Z = 8. Its structure consists of one-dimensional infinite {[Mo3O10]2-}∞ chains linked through {Cu2(H2O)2(4,4‘-bipy)} units. The Mo−O chain contains distorted {MoO6} octahedra connected through corner-sharing oxygen atoms into infinite chains along the c direction and each chain is located in the channel formed by four adjacent crossing chains of {Cu(4,4‘-bipy)(H2O)} n 2 n +. The crystal shows weak conductivity through Mo−O chain along the c direction and insulating property along either a or b direction. Furthermore, a crystalline bimetallic oxide, CuMo3O10, forms when the title compound undergoes thermal treatment in N2 atmosphere after the complete removal of the ligands.

elements.content: Hybrid organic−inorganic materials have become a major research theme in inorganic and materials chemistry. The synergistic interaction between organic and inorganic component leads to complex compositions and diverse structures of the materials, and these materials usually show unusual features and multifunctionalities. The synthetic strategies for controlling structure−function relationship have been extensively investigated by focusing on the property of the diphasic interface and the structural directing role of organic compounds. According to the nature of the bonds between organic and inorganic components, the materials can be divided into two major families in which one exhibits weak bonding while another exhibits strong bonding. The former has been exploited for preparation of some important materials such as zeolites4 and mesoporous materials5 where the organic component (template) can be totally removed by facile calcination or extraction. The latter has also been applied for preparation of hybrids such as biomineralized materials, microporous transition metal phosphates with entrained organic cations, and molybdenum or vanadium oxide subunits modified by organonitrogen ligands or their coordinated metal cations where the framework is usually sustained by the organic component.
elements.clean_text:
Introduction

Hybrid organic-inorganic materials have become a major research theme in inorganic and materials chemistry. The synergistic interaction between organic and inorganic component leads to complex compositions and diverse structures of the materials, and these materials usually show unusual features and multifunctionalities. The synthetic strategies for controlling structure-function relationship have been extensively investigated by focusing on the property of the diphasic interface and the structural directing role of organic compounds. According to the nature of the bonds between organic and inorganic components, the materials can be divided into two major families in which one exhibits weak bonding while another exhibits strong bonding. The former has been exploited for preparation of some important materials such as zeolites4 and mesoporous materials5 where the organic component (template) can be totally removed by facile calcination or extraction. The latter has also been applied for preparation of hybrids such as biomineralized materials, microporous transition metal phosphates with entrained organic cations, and molybdenum or vanadium oxide subunits modified by organonitrogen ligands or their coordinated metal cations where the framework is usually sustained by the organic component.

elements.content: Currently, molybdenum polyoxoanions attract much attention due to their versatile stoichiometry, different structure, and high reactivity. The exploration of a generalized approach for preparation of one-, two-, and three-dimensional organodiamine-templated molybdenum oxides and hybrid bimetallic oxides using hydrothermal methods reported by Zubieta et al. and others further demonstrates the wide variety of molybdenum oxoanion subunits ranging from {MoO4}2- to {Mo8O26}4-, the existence of infinite chains of {MoO6} octahedra with different connecting modes linked through corner-, edge-, and/or face-sharing octahedra, and the influences of ligand and the coordination of metal if containing the secondary metal on the structural change. In this study, we choose 4,4‘-bipyridine (4,4‘-bipy) as a polyfunctional rodlike ligand and copper as a secondary metal to hydrothermally synthesize bipyridine-ligated copper-trimolybdate monohydrate [Cu(4,4‘-bipy)(H2O)(Mo3O10)]·H2O. The crystal structure, conductivity, and thermal decomposition of the title compound are also reported.

elements.content: Synthesis of [Cu(4,4‘-bipy)(H 2 O)(Mo 3 O 10 )] · (H 2 O). A mixture of (NH4)6Mo7O24·4H2O, CuCl2·2H2O, and 4,4‘-bipy in H2O with a molar ratio of 1:2:2:1110 in an autoclave was heated at 150 °C for two weeks under autogenous pressure. After the reaction, the autoclave was slowly cooled to room temperature. Blue crystals in ca. 10% yield were obtained and washed with water. The excess starting materials remained in the solution as unknown species. IR spectrum of the crystal using KBr pellet exhibits intense bands at 490, 658 cm-1, and 820, 887, 918, and 933 cm-1 assigned to ν(Mo−O−Mo) and ν(MoO), respectively, and bands at 1620, 1540, 1420, and 1320 cm-1 assigned to characteristic vibrational modes of 4,4‘-bipyridine.

Experimental Section

 Synthesis of [Cu(4,4‘-bipy)(H  2  O)(Mo  3  O  10  )] ⋅ (H  2  O). A mixture of (NH4)6Mo7O24⋅4H2O, CuCl2⋅2H2O, and 4,4‘-bipy in H2O with a molar ratio of 1:2:2:1110 in an autoclave was heated at 150 °C for two weeks under autogenous pressure. elements.content: X-ray Crystallography. The single crystal of the title compound with dimensions of 0.25 × 0.10 × 0.05 mm3 was carefully selected under an optical microscope and glued to a thin glass fiber with epoxy resin. Crystal structure determination by X-ray diffraction was performed on a Bruker AXS SMART CCD diffractometer equipped with a normal-focus, 2.4-kW, sealed-tube X-ray source with Mo Kα radiation (λ = 0.71073 Å) operating at 50 kV and 30 mA. About 1.3-hemispheres of intensity data were collected at room temperature with a scan width of 0.30° in ω and an exposure time of 30 s per frame. The empirical absorption corrections were based on the equivalent reflections. The structure was solved by direct methods followed by successive difference Fourier methods. All calculations were performed using SHELXTL and SHELXTL-97, and final full-matrix refinements were against F 2.

elements.content: Structural Description. As shown in Figure a, the title compound is constructed from [Mo3O10]2- chains incorporated within the scaffolding by {Cu(4,4-bipy)} n 2 n + subunits. The structure consists of {CuO3N2} square pyramids and {MoO6} octahedra, forming a three-dimensional bimetallic oxide framework with channels occupied by the 4,4‘-bipy ligands. The cationic component forms one-dimensional chains of {CuO3N2} square pyramid linked through bridging bidentate 4,4‘-bipy groups. Each CuII site of the chain is coordinated to one H2O molecule, two terminal oxo groups from the molybdate cluster subunit, and two nitrogen atoms from two 4,4‘-bipy ligands to form slightly distorted square pyramidal coordination with one terminal O atom at the apical position (Figure b). The central Cu atom is displaced by 0.114(1) Å from the equatorial plane defined by N1, N2vi, O1, and O11 atoms toward O8v, and the Cu−N bond distances are 1.949 and 1.974 Å, while the axial Cu−O bond distance is 2.324 Å. The chains exhibit a 27.35° twist between the rings of the bipyridyl units. The two distinct chains along [110] and [001] directions form a right angle or virtual square network. When viewed along the c axis, the {Cu(4,4-bipy)} n 2 n + scaffoldings are linked through {CuO3N2} square pyramid to produce channels of sufficient diameter to accommodate [Mo3O10]2- chains. As shown in Figure c, {MoO6} octahedra form a chain which is structurally analogous to that observed in the one-dimensional (NH4)[Mo3O10]. The infinite zigzag chains of (Mo3O10)2- moiety stretch along the c axis, which is different from the case reported in the one-dimensional molybdenum oxide [Cu2(pyrd)(Mo3O10)].

elements.content: Conductivity. The anisotropic properties of the [Cu(4,4‘-bipy)(H2O)(Mo3O10)]·H2O single crystal can be proved by measuring the conductivity along the specific direction of crystal axis. The voltammetric curves along the c and a or b directions are shown in Figure . The conductivity of the single crystal is approximately4.3 × 10-8 s cm-1 along the c direction and effectively zero along the a and b directions. Molybdenum−copper composite oxides have been of interest as a candidate for cathode materials in high-energy-density secondary batteries, and their conductivity is related to the content of copper, in which the oxide with the composition of Cu0.3MoO3 shows the highest conductivity, ca. 4.16 × 10-2 s cm-1. In the present case, the current passes through the {MoO6} octahedra chains along the c axis and the copper atoms do not involve in the electric conduction. Therefore, only the molybdenum−oxygen chains account for the weak conducting property whereas the copper−bipydine chains parallel to (001) are insulating.

elements.content: Thermal Behavior. As shown in Figure , the thermal decomposition of the title compound under nitrogen exhibits a gradual dehydration in the range from room temperature to 250 °C, accounting for a 2.7% weight loss, which is attributed to the release of the crystalline water (2.56% theoretical weight loss). This process is followed by a consecutive weight loss of ca. 24.2%, which is attributed to the release of an aqua ligand and the decomposition of ligands (24.76%, theoretical weight loss) in the range of 250−370 °C. The mass becomes constant above 370 °C. The total weight loss of 26.9% is consistent with calculated value (27.32%) if CuMo3O10 is the final product. EDX result also indicates Cu/Mo molar ratio of 1:3 remains unchanged.

elements.content: To understand the decomposition process and phase transition, temperature-dependent in situ XRD experiments of the title compound were acquired. In Figure the pattern of the title compound at room temperature displays the characteristic diffraction peaks which can be indexed according to the crystal parameters of [Cu(4,4‘-bipy)(H2O)(Mo3O10)]·H2O. At 200 °C, the pattern shows some changes, indicating the variation of the structure due to the loss of water. The loss of the aqua ligand and the decomposition of bipydine took place between 200 and 400 °C with the appearance of a new set of diffraction peaks which can be indexed according to an orthorhombic phase with parameters of a = 6.795 Å, b = 6.546 Å, and c = 4.285 Å. These diffraction peaks are unchanged until 600 °C and remain upon cooling to room temperature. The found d values are consistent with those calculated from the cell parameters. HRTEM and SAED images provide further evidences to the new phase. SAED (Figure a) shows the nature of single crystal. In a typical TEM image (Figure b), crystal lattice of Mo−Cu composite oxide shows that the distance between two fringes is ca. 0.48 nm compared with d-spacing of (110) in orthorhombic phase of CuMo3O10 and each particle shows the same crystalline orientation. To our knowledge, organoamine ligated bimetallic oxides generally undergo thermal decomposition to form unidentified phase, amorphous phase, or mixture, even though the copper trimolybdate hydrate (CuMo3O10·5H2O) became amorphous under heating treatment. Therefore, the present result indicates that thermal treatment of the hybrid organic−inorganic composite materials may break a new path to obtain crystalline bimetallic oxides.

In Figure  the pattern of the title compound at room temperature displays the characteristic diffraction peaks which can be indexed according to the crystal parameters of [Cu(4,4‘-bipy)(H2O)(Mo3O10)]⋅H2O. At 200 °C, the pattern shows some changes, indicating the variation of the structure due to the loss of water. The loss of the aqua ligand and the decomposition of bipydine took place between 200 and 400 °C with the appearance of a new set of diffraction peaks which can be indexed according to an orthorhombic phase with parameters of a = 6.795 Å, b = 6.546 Å, and c = 4.285 Å. These diffraction peaks are unchanged until 600 °C and remain upon cooling to room temperature. The found d values are consistent with those calculated from the cell parameters. HRTEM and SAED images provide further evidences to the new phase. SAED (Figure a) shows the nature of single  crystal. In a typical TEM image (Figure b), crystal lattice of Mo-Cu composite oxide shows that the distance between two fringes is ca. 0.48 nm compared with d-spacing of (110) in orthorhombic phase of CuMo3O10 and each particle shows the same crystalline orientation. To our knowledge, organoamine ligated bimetallic oxides generally undergo thermal decomposition to form unidentified phase, amorphous phase, or mixture, even though the copper trimolybdate hydrate (CuMo3O10⋅5H2O) became amorphous under heating treatment. Therefore, the present result indicates that thermal treatment of the hybrid organic-inorganic composite materials may break a new path to obtain crystalline bimetallic oxides.

elements.clean_text:
Conclusions

The hydrothermal technique has been exploited to prepare a new hybrid organic-inorganic material of bipyridine-ligated copper-trimolybdate monohydrate [Cu(4,4‘-bipy)(H2O)(Mo3O10)]⋅H2O. The compound exhibits three-dimensional framework, which contains one-dimensional infinite {[Mo3O10]2- chains located in the channel formed by four adjacent crossing chains of {Cu(4,4‘-bipy)(H2O)} n  2  n  +. The anisotropic property of the crystal has been observed by measuring conductivity of the crystal along different directions. The title compound undergoes thermal decomposition to form a new crystalline phase of a bimetallic oxide, CuMo3O10, which has been characterized by XRD, TEM and SAED.

cln_elements.content: Synthesis of [Cu(4,4‘-bipy)(H 2 O)(Mo 3 O 10 )] · (H 2 O). A mixture of (NH4)6Mo7O24·4H2O, CuCl2·2H2O, and 4,4‘-bipy in H2O with a molar ratio of 1:2:2:1110 in an autoclave was heated at 150 °C for two weeks under autogenous pressure. After the reaction, the autoclave was slowly cooled to room temperature. Blue crystals in ca. 10% yield were obtained and washed with water. The excess starting materials remained in the solution as unknown species. IR spectrum of the crystal using KBr pellet exhibits intense bands at 490, 658 cm-1, and 820, 887, 918, and 933 cm-1 assigned to ν(Mo−O−Mo) and ν(MoO), respectively, and bands at 1620, 1540, 1420, and 1320 cm-1 assigned to characteristic vibrational modes of 4,4‘-bipyridine.

cln_elements.content:
The hydrothermal reaction of (NH4)6Mo7O24·4H2O, CuCl2·2H2O, and 4,4‘-bipyridine yields bipyridine-ligated copper-trimolybdate monohydrate [Cu(4,4‘-bipy)(H2O)(Mo3O10)]·H2O in the monoclinic system with space group of C 2/c and cell parameters of a = 15.335(2) Å, b = 15.535(2) Å, c = 15.106(2) Å, β = 101.162(2)°, V = 3530.7(9) Å3, and Z = 8. Its structure consists of one-dimensional infinite {[Mo3O10]2-}∞ chains linked through {Cu2(H2O)2(4,4‘-bipy)} units. The Mo−O chain contains distorted {MoO6} octahedra connected through corner-sharing oxygen atoms into infinite chains along the c direction and each chain is located in the channel formed by four adjacent crossing chains of {Cu(4,4‘-bipy)(H2O)} n 2 n +. The crystal shows weak conductivity through Mo−O chain along the c direction and insulating property along either a or b direction. Furthermore, a crystalline bimetallic oxide, CuMo3O10, forms when the title compound undergoes thermal treatment in N2 atmosphere after the complete removal of the ligands.

Thermal Behavior. As shown in Figure , the thermal decomposition of the title compound under nitrogen exhibits a gradual dehydration in the range from room temperature to 250 °C, accounting for a 2.7% weight loss, which is attributed to the release of the crystalline water (2.56% theoretical weight loss). This process is followed by a consecutive weight loss of ca. 24.2%, which is attributed to the release of an aqua ligand and the decomposition of ligands (24.76%, theoretical weight loss) in the range of 250−370 °C. The mass becomes constant above 370 °C. The total weight loss of 26.9% is consistent with calculated value (27.32%) if CuMo3O10 is the final product. EDX result also indicates Cu/Mo molar ratio of 1:3 remains unchanged.
